Gille's battlecruiser design called for a displacement of {{convert|28247|MT|abbr=on}} on a hull that was {{convert|205|m|sp=us}} [[length between perpendiculars|long between perpendiculars]], with a [[beam (nautical)|beam]] of {{convert|27|m|ftin|abbr=on}} at the waterline and an average [[draft (hull)|draft]] of {{convert|9.03|m|ftin|abbr=on}}. The [[Freeboard (nautical)|freeboard]] forward was {{convert|7.15|m|ftin|abbr=on}}, and aft was {{convert|4.65|m|abbr=on}}. The hull lines of the ships proved to be highly efficient in tank tests during the design process. Due to the extreme weight of the main battery turrets at the bow and stern, the hull had to be strengthened to handle the strain. Very strong longitudinal bracing was incorporated, and the inner and outer skins of the hull was thickened to reinforce the bracings. The ships' expected [[metacentric height]] was {{convert|1.03|m|abbr=on}}, comparable to the British ''Lion'' class. Each ship would be crewed by 41&nbsp;officers and 1,258&nbsp;enlisted men.<ref name=L152>Le Masson, p. 152</ref>

The ships would have been equipped with four sets of [[steam turbine]]s rated at {{convert|80000|shp|lk=in}} powered by fifty-two coal-fired [[Belleville boiler]]s. Each propeller shaft was connected to a high-pressure turbine, a medium-pressure [[geared turbine]], and a low-pressure turbine for forward steaming, and a [[direct drive turbine]] for steaming in reverse. The ships' top speed was to have been 28&nbsp;knots. The ships would have been supplied with {{convert|2833|MT|abbr=on}} of coal and {{convert|630|MT|abbr=on}} of fuel oil for supplementary oil firing. At maximum speed, the ships could have cruised for {{convert|1660|nmi|lk=in}}; at {{convert|20.3|kn|abbr=on}}, the range increased to {{convert|4240|nmi|abbr=on}}, an at a more economical {{convert|15|kn|abbr=on}}, the range grew to {{convert|6300|nmi|abbr=on}}.<ref name=GG200/><ref name=L152/>

The ships' main armament was composed of twelve [[340mm/45 Modèle 1912 gun]]s in three quadruple turrets, the same as in the contemporary French battleships of the ''Normandie'' class. One turret was placed forward, and the other two were placed in a [[superfire|superfiring pair]], all on the centerline.<ref name=GG200/><ref name=L152/> The guns had a range of {{convert|16000|m|abbr=on|yd}} and had a [[rate of fire]] of two rounds per minute. The shells were {{convert|540|kg|adj=on}} armor-piercing rounds and were fired with a [[muzzle velocity]] of {{convert|800|m/s|sp=us}}.<ref>Friedman, p. 207</ref> A secondary battery of twenty-four [[Canon de 138 mm Modèle 1910 Naval gun|138.6&nbsp;mm /55 Modèle 1910]] guns mounted in [[casemate]]s was planned for defense against [[torpedo boat]]s.<ref name=GG200/><ref name=L152/> These guns fired a {{convert|36.5|kg|abbr=on}} shell at a muzzle velocity of {{convert|830|m/s|abbr=on}}.<ref>Friedman, p. 225</ref> The armament was rounded out by six [[torpedo tube]]s of undetermined diameter, all submerged in the ships' hulls.<ref name=GG200/><ref name=L152/>

The armor protecting both the main [[armored belt]] [[amidships]] and the main battery turrets was {{convert|270|mm|abbr=on|1}} thick. The lower armored deck was {{convert|20|mm|abbr=on}} thick, with {{convert|50|mm|abbr=on}} of armor plating on the sloped sides. The casemate guns were protected with {{convert|180|mm|abbr=on|1}} of steel armor. The ships were also equipped with a 20&nbsp;mm thick [[torpedo bulkhead]].<ref name=GG200/><ref name=L152/>

