In 1913, the Naval College had several of its students submit design studies for a fast capital ship. The class was given a displacement of {{convert|27500|MT|abbr=on}} as a limit on size; all of the officers opted to design either fast or slow battleships, with the exception of Lieutenant Durand-Viel, who chose instead to create a design for a battlecruiser. Durand-Viel drew up a pair of designs, which were evaluated by the General Staff in June 1914.<ref name=L152/> He saw his ships forming a fast division of the battle fleet capable of encircling an enemy squadron; as with Gille's design, this required heavy armament and armor to permit the ships to engage battleships.<ref name=L155>Le Masson, p. 155</ref>

=== Project "A" characteristics ===
Durand-Viel's first battlecruiser design, "A", was built on a displacement of {{convert|27500|MT|abbr=on}}. The hull was {{convert|210|m|sp=us}} [[length at the waterline|long at the waterline]], with a beam of {{convert|27|m|abbr=on}} at the waterline and an average [[draft (hull)|draft]] of {{convert|8.7|m|abbr=on}}. The ships would have been equipped with four sets of direct drive turbines rated at {{convert|74000|shp|lk=in}} powered by twenty-four double-ended Belleville boilers that burned both coal and oil. The ships' top speed was to have been {{convert|27|kn}}. The ships would have been supplied with {{convert|1810|MT|abbr=on}} of coal and {{convert|1050|MT|abbr=on}} of fuel oil . The ships could have cruised for {{convert|3500|nmi|lk=in}} at {{convert|16|kn|abbr=on}}, with enough fuel for an additional six hours for combat speeds.<ref name=GG200/><ref name=L154>Le Masson, p. 154</ref>

The ships' main armament was composed of eight 340mm/45 Modèle 1912 guns in two quadruple turrets, the same as in the contemporary French battleships of the ''Normandie'' class. Both turrets were placed on the centerline, on either end of the ship.<ref name=GG200/><ref name=L152/> A secondary battery of twenty-four 138.6&nbsp;mm Modèle 1910 guns mounted in [[casemate]]s was planned for defense against torpedo boats. Four {{convert|47|mm|abbr=on}} saluting guns were also to be equipped. The armament was rounded out by four {{convert|450|mm|abbr=on}} torpedo tubes, all submerged in the ships' hulls. The main armored belt amidships  was {{convert|280|mm|abbr=on}} thick, slightly thinner than the belt on the ''Normandie''-class battleships. The rest of the ship's armor was very similar to that of the ''Normandie'' class.<ref name=GG200/><ref name=L154/>

